what level of education does the father of the student have mother's occupation - current occupation of the mother of the student father's occupation - current occupation of the father of the student educational special needs - whether the student needs education special needs or not debtor - whether the student has debt or not tuition fees up to date - whether the student's tuition fees are up to date or not scholarship holder - whether the student holds a scholarship or not unemployment rate - the current unemployment rate of the economy inflation rate - the current inflation rate of the economy gdp - the current gdp of the economy application mode - From the subplots, we can see that most females will end up graduating, while for males the distribution is more even while more in favor of dropping out. From the education special needs plot, we can see that students with none are more likely to graduate. We also see that very few students need educational special needs. From the scholarship holder plot, We can see that whether or not the student is a scholarship holder or not, both have higher graduate counts. We see that the international graph is very similar to the educational special needs graph. In the displaced graph, We see that displaced students will have a higher chance of graduating than dropping out.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

X=student.drop(['Target'], axis=1)
y=student['Target']

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(X)
student['Cluster'] = clusters

cluster_analysis = student.groupby('Cluster')['Target'].mean()
print(cluster_analysis)

pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=clusters, cmap='viridis', marker='o', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Clusters Visualization')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.colorbar(label='Cluster')
plt.show()
